For nearly 10 years, the government investigated Risen and demanded that he reveal his alleged sources.
In this context, he became a symbol of the government's pattern of prosecuting whistleblowers and spying on journalists.
According to the First Amendment, the media has the right to publish confidential information.
But it is impossible to exercise this right when the media do not receive this information and when they cannot protect the identity of the brave individuals who disclose it.
So when the government came knocking on Risen, he did something that many brave reporters had done before him: he refused and stated that he would rather go to prison.
From 2007 to 2015, Risen lived with the risk of going to prison.
But then, just days before the trial, something extraordinary happened.
Suddenly, although they had claimed for years that it was essential for their case, the government's demands on Risen were dropped.
The reason: In the age of electronic surveillance, reporters and sources can hide less and less.
Instead of failing and forcing Risen to testify, his digital footprints could also take care of that for him.
And so the investigators secretly obtained his phone records without his consent,
just like his email data, financial and banking information, his credit report, and even travel records with the list of his flights.
