Today, there is communication software that did not exist when Risen wrote his book, and it is significantly more secure than regular emails or phone calls.
One such technology is SecureDrop, an open-source submission system for whistleblowers that was originally developed by the late internet activist Aaron Swartz, and has since been further developed by the Freedom of the Press Foundation, where I work.
Instead of sending an email, you go to a messaging website, like the one here from the Washington Post.
There, you can upload documents or send information, just like with any ordinary contact form.
These are then encrypted and stored on a server to which only the respective news agency has access.
Therefore, the government can no longer secretly obtain information, and many of the details it would request would not be available from the outset.
SecureDrop is just a small part of the whole effort to protect press freedom in the 21st century.
